 (stats1.errors_aaah == 0) stats1.errortime_aaah = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors_aaah = stats1.errors_aaah+1\'b1; end\n\t\tif (digging_ref !== ( digging_ref ^ digging_dut ^ digging_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_digging == 0) stats1.errortime_digging = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors_digging = stats1.errors_digging+1\'b1; end\n\n\tend\n\n   // add timeout after 100K cycles\n   initial begin\n     #1000000\n     $display("TIMEOUT");\n     $finish();\n   end\n\nendmodule\n\n\n</testbench>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.ASSISTANT: 'assistant'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='{\n    "reasoning": "1. **Identify States**: The Lemming\'s behavior depends on its current walking direction (Left or Right), whether it is currently falling, or whether it is currently digging. \\n    - `WALK_LEFT`: Walking left on ground.\\n    - `WALK_RIGHT`: Walking right on ground.\\n    - `FALLING_L`: Falling after being in `WALK_LEFT`.\\n    - `FALLING_R`: Falling after being in `WALK_RIGHT`.\\n    - `DIGGING_L`: Digging while moving left (though the spec implies digging doesn\'t have a direction, the Lemming resumes its direction after. However, the spec says \'digging is a useful thing\' and \'it will continue digging until it reaches the other side\'. Since direction is preserved, we need to know which way it was going to resume).\\n    - `DIGGING_R`: Digging while moving right.\\n    - `DIGGING_FALL_L`: Falling after digging while moving left.\\n    - `DIGGING_FALL_R`: Falling after digging while moving right.\\n    Wait, let\'s refine: \\n    States: \\n    - `WALK_L`, `WALK_R` (Walking on ground)\\n    - `FALL_L`, `FALL_R` (Falling, direction is L or R)\\n    - `DIG_L`, `DIG_R` (Digging, direction is L or R)\\n    - `FALL_DIG_L`, `FALL_DIG_R` (Falling after digging, direction is L or R)\\n    Actually, the spec says: \'A Lemming can dig if it is currently walking on ground... and will continue digging until it reaches the other side (ground=0). At that point... it will fall (aaah!), then continue walking in its original direction once it hits ground again.\'\\n    This means: \\n    - `WALK_L` -> (dig=1) -> `DIG_L` -> (ground=0) -> `FALL_DIG_L` -> (ground=1) -> `WALK_L`.\\n    - `WALK_L` -> (ground=0) -> `FALL_L` -> (ground=1) -> `WALK_L`.\\n    - `WALK_L` -> (bump_right) -> `WALK_R`.\\n    - `WALK_L` -> (bump_left) -> `WALK_R` (spec says \'if bumped on both sides... it will still switch directions\').\\n    - `WALK_L` -> (bump_left) -> `WALK_R` and (bump_right) -> `WALK_L`? No, \'If it\'s bumped on the left, it will walk right. If it\'s bumped on the right, it will walk left.\' If both happen, it switches. Let\'s assume `bump_left != bump_right` is the standard, but if both are 1, it switches. Actually, the spec says \'it will still switch directions\'. This implies if current is L, and it hits both, it goes to R. If current is R and it hits both, it goes to L.\\n    \\n    2. **Precedence Rules**: \\n    - Fall (ground=0) > Dig (dig=1) > Switch direction (bump).\\n    - While falling, bumps are ignored. \\n    - While digging, bumps are ignored.\\n    \\n    3. **Transitions for WALK_L**:\\n    - If ground=0: transition to `FALL_L`.\\n    - Else if dig=1: transition to `DIG_L`.\\n    - Else if bump_left or bump_right: transition to `WALK_R` (if bump_left/right/both triggers switch).\\n    - Else: stay `WALK_L`.\\n    Wait, \'If it\'s bumped on the left, it will walk right. If it\'s bumped on the right, it will walk left.\'\\n    If `bump_left == 1` and `bump_right == 0` -> switch to `WALK_R`.\\n    If `bump_right == 1` and `bump_left == 0` -> switch to `WALK_L`? No, that\'s not right. \\n    Let\'s re-read: \'If a Lemming is bumped on the left... it will walk right. If it\'s bumped on the right... it will walk left.\'\\n    So:\\n    If `bump_left` and `!bump_right`: direction = Right.\\n    If `!bump_left` and `bump_right`: direction = Left.\\n    If `bump_left` and `bump_right`: direction = switch (L->R, R->L).\\n    If `!bump_left` and `!bump_right`: direction = no change.\\n\\n    4. **Implementation Details**:\\n    - Moore machine: outputs depend only on state.\\n    - `areset` is asynchronous, positive edge.\\n    - `walk_left` is 1 in `WALK_L`, `FALL_L`, `DIG_L`, `FALL_DIG_L`? No, \'walking left\' is a state of being on ground. The spec says \'Lemmings can be in one of two states: walking left or walking right\'. Falling and digging are \'in addition to\' walking and falling. This implies `walk_left` and `walk_right` are mutually exclusive and only 1 when on ground and not digging/falling.\\n    Actually, \'when ground=0, the Lemming will fall and say aaah!\'. This implies `aaah` is the output for falling. \\n    \'A Lemming can dig... and will continue digging until it reaches the other side... At that point... it will fall (aaah!)\'.\\n    So outputs are: `walk_left`, `walk_right`, `aaah`, `digging`.\\n    - `walk_left`: 1 when state is `WALK_L`.\\n    - `walk_right`: 1 when state is `WALK_R`.\\n    - `aaah`: 1 when state is `FALL_L`, `FALL_R`, `FALL_DIG_L`, `FALL_DIG_R`.\\n    - `digging`: 1 when state is `DIG_L`, `DIG_R`.\\n\\n    5. **Refined States**:\\n    - `S_WALK_L` (out: walk_left=1)\\n    - `S_WALK_R` (out: walk_right=1)\\n    - `S_FALL_L` (out: aaah=1)\\n    - `S_FALL_R` (out: aaah=1)\\n    - `S_DIG_L` (out: digging=1)\\n    - `S_DIG_R` (out: digging=1)\\n    - `S_FALL_DIG_L` (out: aaah=1)\\n    - `S_FALL_DIG_R` (out: aaah=1)\\n\\n    6. **Logic for Switch**:\\n    If `bump_left` and `bump_right`: direction = !direction.\\n    If `bump_left`: direction = Right.\\n    If `bump_right`: direction = Left.\\n    \\n    7. **Advices to avoid syntax error**:\\n    - Ensure all `always @(*)` blocks are complete (assign all outputs).\\n    - Use `logic` for all signals.\\n    - Ensure `areset` is used in `always @(posedge clk or posedge areset)`.\\n    - Check that `aaah` and `digging` outputs are strictly Moore (calculated from state).",\n    "module": 